rows: A number of Australian-language 'pelican' terms contain 'hip', a reference to their awkward walk [P Sutton]. KYal /biluwarra/, probably mistranslated as 'spoonbill', is a loan from this.
large shell used for boiling water
night owl (sp[presumed barn owl]) & night owl (sp [presumed small]) & night owl (sp)
/murrabal/ is Nyungkul dialect, not KYal proper. Loan status in GYim is a possibility because of failure of V2 to lengthen.
Fights w. taipan; its flesh (it eats roots of the /yiranh/ tree to cure snakebite) is a cure for snakebite
kookaburra [two spp, no further info as to which is which]
/gugaa/ (and poss. also /gurruulga) is probably sound-symbolic; /gugaa/ could be regularly cognate w Duungidjawu /kukaka/; resembles reflexs of pPaman *kungkaka but cannot be a continuation of this.
To KYal and Flinders Island; poss. wider distribution. The /kurr/ part occurrs in a widespread reduplicative pattern imitative of the call.
Attested also in Biri (Maric) and Yugambeh. Long V2 in Yimithirr (GHav; KLH recorded short V2) indicates former 3rd syllable, apparently not supported in other evidence except nearby Almura
curlew, night bird sp. & calew [stress 2nd syll: local English pronunciation of curlew]
KYal /kuyir/ is poss a loan from this.
vine sp, edible (Avicennia officinalis, but poss. Vigna lutea)

/gudaa/ 'dog' and /yinil/ 'wild, timid' continue from pPaman *kutaka and *yini- respectively.
KYal /girbaji/; expected GYim reflex of *kirpaci would be **kir(r)paath/y.
*kuyu or *kuya; not clear what if any the etymological relation of /kuuju/ is. /guyuu/ is 'milk, breast'.

The respect term for any crocodile or large lizard is wayin.
Questionable: /thandaar/ poss. to Muruwari /thantay/ 'frog'.  /thanamundi/ is unique, but garrgurr 'sand frog' is cognate w KYal karrkurr 'green frog'
/buunhtha/ 'male turtle' and /maamiingu/ 'female' poss. define a taxon.
sand goanna & goanna living on sandhill & sand goanna sp
Flinders I. south along East Coast, to Maric generally. Also in Dyirbal, Warrgamay, Nyawaygi.  Variant *cakay. Poss. loan in GYim or other northern languages.
/ganhaarr/ is apparently generic for all goannas, water lizards, and crocodiles
Reflexes in other lgs mean 'burnt-over ground'.
As *punti+, pPama-Maric. /yiijin/ is cognate w KYim /yiljun/.

scrubhen & scrubhen (small) [possibly synonymous and phonological alternants]
These are probably variants of the same word. Sound correspondences not clear; loss of *rr is found also in Flinders Island /thuka/.
